const v19ReadA={id:"v19-read-a",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 69-72",title:"Rainfall Threshold Warnings",description:"A mountain municipality issued landslide warnings whenever daily rainfall exceeded one fixed threshold. Several warnings were unnecessary in dry months, while one slope failed after moderate rain following a week of saturation. Geologists combined short-term intensity, seven-day accumulated rain, slope history, and ground sensors. They set different alert levels and required field confirmation when sensors behaved abnormally. The revised system reduced false alarms in a trial year, but officials avoided claiming perfect prediction because sensor gaps, local drainage, and rare failure mechanisms remained.",alt:"Passage about replacing one daily-rain threshold with multiple rainfall, slope, and ground indicators plus field confirmation, reducing false alarms without claiming perfect landslide prediction."};
const v19ReadB={id:"v19-read-b",kind:"passage",label:"Babasahin para sa Aytem 73-76",title:"Bangko ng Binhi",description:"Nagtipon ang samahan ng magsasaka ng binhi mula sa iba't ibang lokal na uri. Sa unang taniman, mataas ang dami ng ipinamahagi ngunit may ilang binhing mahina ang pagtubo dahil hindi pareho ang pagpapatuyo at pag-iimbak. Nagpatupad ang samahan ng moisture test, malinaw na batch label, at maliit na germination sample bago ilabas ang bawat lot. Itinala rin kung saang bukid nagmula at bumalik ang binhi. Tumaas ang germination rate, ngunit hindi nila ginamit iyon bilang tanging batayan ng ani dahil nakaaapekto rin ang lupa, panahon, peste, at pangangalaga.",alt:"Teksto tungkol sa community seed bank na nagdagdag ng moisture test, batch labels, germination sampling, at provenance records matapos makitang hindi pantay ang pagtubo, habang kinikilalang maraming salik ang ani."};
const v19ReadC={id:"v19-read-c",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 77-80",title:"Warranty-Based Maintenance",description:"A city bought pumps from the lowest bidder but recorded frequent repair expenses during the first year. The procurement file listed a warranty, yet work orders did not identify whether each failure was covered, and staff sometimes paid for repairs before notifying the supplier. The city linked asset serial numbers, warranty terms, failure reports, and supplier response deadlines in one maintenance register. Covered repairs were then referred before payment approval. Costs declined, but managers noted that the register could not show whether the original purchase represented best value without comparing reliability, energy use, downtime, and purchase price across models.",alt:"Passage about linking pump serial numbers, warranty terms, failures, and supplier deadlines so covered repairs are referred before payment, while noting that best value requires broader lifecycle comparisons."};
